narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Learn about some elements of 21st techniques from Ardour to supercollider.
Music production techniques and some supercollider coding skills.
Learned a lot about sound and production

I learned so much from this course. Coming in, I had no knowledge about computer music techniques, or electronic music as a genre, but leaving this course I have a solid knowledge about music production, recording techniques, and both how to use a DAW and code music on SuperCollider. I definitely developed perseverance because a lot of the concepts covered in class were difficult for me to wrap my mind around as someone with little coding experience, but I ended up becoming comfortable enough with coding to code my Final Project!
I learned a bit about music production and sound synthesis.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: The production part is really fun and the projects were exciting, but the coding was hard to learn and there wasn't a ton of time for teaching it, especially given people's inexperience with coding.

I think the strengths are how hands on it is, you have to make 2 music production pieces. The weaknesses are with Supercollider, as someone with no knowledge of coding going into it, he never really taught us the basics of coding and what coding really is, which made it hard to keep up as we went pretty fast into supercollider.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, the fun is worth the struggle to learn on your own I think.
Professor is a bit of a stickler but interesting topics none the less

I would recommend this course to another student who already has an interest in music, music production, or code because I know it would be both interesting and mentally stimulating for them, as it was for me. However, I would tell students as well that, despite it being a first-year seminar, it is intense and definitely not a gut QR credit course.
Yes if your interested in not just music production but also coding on supercollider, and are willing to put in a lot of work outside of class.
